Load the tidyverse

library("tidyverse")
library("janitor")

Data

For this assignment, we will use data from a study on elephants and the effects of poaching on tusk size.

Reference: Chiyo, Patrick I., Vincent Obanda, and David K. Korir. Illegal tusk harvest and the decline of tusk size in the African elephant. Ecology and Evolution 5, 22: 52165229 (2015). Data deposited at Dryad Digital Repository.

1. Before starting data analysis, read the abstract of the paper to get an idea of the questions being asked. In 2-3 sentences, describe what the study is testing and the variables involved.
The study looks at after large ivory harvests if tusk size goes down in future generations. The variables are sample years (1966-1968, late 1970s, early 1980s, mid 1990s), shoulder height, tusk size, sex.

2. Load elephants.csv and store it as a new object called elephants.

elephants <- read_csv("data/elephants.csv") %>% clean_names()

5. Use mutate() Change the variables years_of_sample_collection, elephant_id, and sex to factors. Be sure to store the output as a new dataframe and use it for the remaining questions.

elephants_factors <- elephants %>% 
  mutate(across(c("years_of_sample_collection", "elephant_id", "sex"), as.factor))

6. From which years were data collected? Show the sample periods below.

elephants_factors %>%

8. What is the mean, median, and standard deviation for age of males and females included in the study? Separate the results by year of sample collection. Does the sampling look even between years and sexes?
The sampling doesnt look even between years and sexes- the mean age got larger for males (slightly larger for females), min age got larger for both males and females, and standard deviation got larger for males and smaller for females.

elephants_factors %>% 
  filter(sex=="m", years_of_sample_collection=="1966-68") %>% 
  summarize(mean_age=mean(estimated_age_years, na.rm=T),
            min_age=min(estimated_age_years, na.rm=T),
            sd_age=sd(estimated_age_years, na.rm=T))

9. Is age (independent variable) a positive predictor of tusk length (dependent variable)? Create a plot that shows the relationship between these variables and add a linear model fit line.
Yes, as elephants get older tusk length gets longer.

ggplot(data=elephants_factors,
       mapping=aes(x=estimated_age_years, y=tusk_length_in_cm))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method=lm,se=T)+
  labs(title="Age vs Tusk Length", x="Age", y="Tusk Length")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 182 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_smooth()`).
## Warning: Removed 182 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_point()`).

10. Is shoulder height (independent variable) a positive predictor of tusk length (dependent variable)? Create a plot that shows the relationship between these variables and add a linear model fit line.
Yes, as shoulder height gets larger tusk length gets longer as well.

ggplot(data=elephants_factors,

11. The authors argue that because poachers preferentially target elephants with large tusks, this has resulted in a decrease in average tusk length. Is this supported by the data? Show your code and calculations below.
This is supported by the data - the average tusk length in the 60s was 96.9cm, and in the 2000s it was 77.2cm.

names(elephants)
## [1] "years_of_sample_collection" "elephant_id"               
## [3] "sex"                        "estimated_age_years"       
## [5] "shoulder_height_in_cm"      "tusk_length_in_cm"         
## [7] "tusk_circumference_in_cm"
elephants_factors %>% 
  filter(years_of_sample_collection=="1966-68") %>% 
  summarize(mean_tusk_length_60=mean(tusk_length_in_cm, na.rm=T))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##   mean_tusk_length_60
##                 <dbl>
## 1                96.9
elephants_factors %>% 
  filter(years_of_sample_collection=="2005-13") %>% 
  summarize(mean_tusk_length_20=mean(tusk_length_in_cm, na.rm=T))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##   mean_tusk_length_20
##                 <dbl>
## 1                77.2

12. Male elephants reach effective sexual maturity at 25 years while females are sexually mature at 12 years. Make a new dataframe that extracts only the males and females at sexual maturity. Then, make a plot that shows the range of tusk length between the two sample periods for these mature elephants.

names(elephants)
## [1] "years_of_sample_collection" "elephant_id"               
## [3] "sex"                        "estimated_age_years"       
## [5] "shoulder_height_in_cm"      "tusk_length_in_cm"         
## [7] "tusk_circumference_in_cm"
elephants_mature <- elephants_factors %>% 
  filter((sex=="m" & estimated_age_years>=25)|(sex=="f" & estimated_age_years>=12))
elephants_mature %>% 
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=years_of_sample_collection, y=tusk_length_in_cm))+
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title="Tusk Length for Mature Elephants",
       x="Years of Sample Collection",
       y="Tusk Length (cm)")
## Warning: Removed 44 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_boxplot()`).
